tips.text: One of the Best Bah Kut Teh,imo. I totally love their soup, and side dishes of deepfried doughsticks, peanuts & salted veggies! I've considered this as a gem among my fav foodhunts in town! :)

One of the places to be 'lost in time' for bookworms and coffee lovers in Singapore! I love the coffee, lovely service, sofas, books and the cakes - in that order! Price is okay for a frequenter.
While it’s easy to skip straight to the cuts, don’t overlook the luscious pan-roasted Maine lobster with black truffle sabayon – perhaps the most unassuming dish on the menu.
This is likely one of the most overrated places in Singapore; mostly by expats. It's expensive and every piece of sushi has frozen crab meat filler.
It's not pancetta but who gives a fork when it's so baconlicious. Honestly I could have one more plate of this al dente masterpiece. Nevermind that it's a work-weekday.

formattedAddress: Bgain 22 Old Street Coffee House (22 Havelock Rd. #01-669.)

tips.text: The pop up Chye Tow Kway guy here in the pre-dawn to morning hours does a very good white carrot cake. Don't come too late though. I hear he sometimes runs out by 8am.
The chilled vermicelli looks plain but don't be deceived by its look, it's really very tasty. The lime and savory taste is really very catchy.
Grab a seat at the wine bar – you can choose from over 100 Italian bottles – to witness the pies being cooked to crispy, bubbly perfection.
Get the wagyu beef cheek! That pomme purée is absolutely divine.
Great view of the Marina Bay Sands. Nice open view at the upstairs bar.
Brown rice salad with some chicken and assorted veggies is good here. Really healthy options, but nice big portions also.
Place to go if you want oldies songs to go with the shanghainese food. Popular during the weekends.
Tasty and good value omakase if you don't mind early 6pm seating. Will be back.
don't let the waiter/waitress recommed for you as you will be surprise for the price!

tips.text: Chili crab is great; black pepper crab is better! Great food, great service :)
Drinks, and the baristas, are clever & may be the place to surround yourself in, on weekends. It has terrific 360 views & happy chatter. It makes for a good perch, stokes writers & un-blues. Fave.

Meat eaters can escape Singapore mediocrity and find Le Bistrot du Sommelier for a reminder of how it's meant to be. Loads of top wines as well. Get a table beforehand and thank me later.
Great open air views of Boat Quay. Cocktails are not too bad, the Cuba cocktail slips down very nicely.
Happy Hour Mortini Nights every Mon-Fri from 5-7pm. The martinis are large, good, and reasonably priced (around $12) with free steak sandwiches on top. Good to go early cos the place fills up fast!
Steaks were good. But on the pricey side. And extremely irritating waiters who keep trying to get us to order more.
Better than average but prefer Everton park's Ji Xiang Ang Ku Kway which has thinner skin.

Diner done up like a little beach shack. Okinawan food is influenced by Chinese and Thai cuisine; their specialty here is definitely the large melting slabs of pork belly braised in soy sauce.
